segments.text: How are you doing?
Today is November the 16th.
And I am visiting with Dr. Phil Limbacher, professor emeritus of educational curriculum and instruction.
And he was appointed to Texas A&M in 1969.
And we're going to talk about his perceptions of the College of Education since its inception, which happens to be in 1969, the same year that you started.
And I would like to know,
a little bit about how you perceived the changes during the time that you were involved with the college.
I came to the college, as you indicated earlier, the very first day that it was an official college, a separate college of education.
And I never regretted it.
I came to it from the College of Education at the University of Illinois.
And my first perceptions and the reason I was drawn to it was the, I guess for want of anything better, the collegial atmosphere you had.
Without denigrating the University of Illinois, it was more of a dog-eat-dog kind of society.

faculty carved out a small domain of the discipline and felt that it was theirs and theirs only to mine and if anybody moved into it there was a great deal of cat-and-dog fighting and I did not see that down here and I hope that the college avoids that type of
attitude as we move along.
That was my first revealing change between the two colleges.
Just as an aside, one of the things that was amusing to me, the observation of Labor Day at Champaign-Urbana was a holiday.
the observation of Labor Day at Texas A&M was a duty day.
And I recall very vividly the movers had moved and were moving all of our belongings into our newly purchased home in Bryan.
And my wife was trying to handle the problem when I was at the university working.
So I remember
old Dean Hubert coming along at about that time and visiting with me and facetiously saying, what was I doing here?
Why wasn't I somewhere else?
Did Dean Hubert recruit you, or how did you happen to come to A&M?
I had become less than enamored with the climate in Illinois, and my wife's home
is down in the valley, and I spent a good deal of World War II fighting it here in the state, which was a very much nicer place to fight World War II than most.
And I enjoyed the state and was hoping to retire from the military to it.
And I had put in for positions.
Texas A&M had advertised a position, and the University of Texas had advertised a position.
And I can give you a little anecdote to show why I am very definitely opposed to Texas, the University of Texas.
And it's also an indication of how far our society has gone.
I made the applications and received a very short and terse letter from the University of Texas indicating that
At this time, the university was not recruiting people of my age bracket.
I was too old for the position.
I don't know.
I was 50-some-what, I guess, at the time.
I came to this thing a little later than usual.
University of Texas A&M, on the other hand, and the letter was signed by, I think, Glenn Johnson, who was the department head at the time, indicating that the position had been filled,
He would keep my application on file.
And the position I was looking for at that time was student teaching placement.
And what little expertise I had was in the area of using videotapes.
Micro-teaching, they called it at that time, which was a really useful way of breaking in a new teacher.
And then I recall we were returning from the picnic on the 4th of July and the phone was ringing and Glenn was calling and wanted to know if I could come down.
And I was very pleased to indicate I was able to come down.
And we came down and I subsequently discovered that the reason the position was open, the occupant of a position
I had gotten a little cross-purposes with the local public school officials.
And evidently, the decision was made that perhaps that individual ought to seek other pastures.
So that opened the position, and I was very, very pleased.
And I came as an assistant professor, which was the position I held at the University of Illinois.
Because as you know, I came out and retired in 67 from the military.
I finished my degree.
and then was teaching there at the university for a year.
So that's why I was a little older than the average.
An organization called SOTA, Students Older Than Average.
Yes, I heard about that one.
And that didn't go over too well down here.
No, I heard about that too.
I encountered that when I tried to get a dorm room, and they said they had one for SOTAs, you know, a floor, a special floor, and I kissed that.
So I feel that category, so I know how you feel.
Okay.
Now I can dribble on like that, but I'm sure you've got another focus.
Well, that was, you know, how you got here was one.
And then once you were here and you began as an assistant professor, there were phenomenal changes between 1969 and the year you retired.
You served in a lot of different positions.
Can you just elaborate a little bit on some of the major changes and what you think brought them about?
I know women was one of the big ones that everybody refers to, but.
a little bit about administration, because you did work under two different administrators, and the changes that occurred as a result of that, possibly.
The initial start of 69, as you would expect, we were still floundering around, and there were some organizational problems.
But basically, in the
The small area that I was interested in was in the secondary education, and they were divided as they are still now, secondary and elementary education.
Major change at the start in the area that I was interested in, which is the student teaching aspects of it.
When I first started in 69, the university was paying a very small stipend
for the cooperating teacher, or supervisor of student teaching.
And then I think Senate Bill 12, I'm not sure, but you can maybe check that out, which was a change in the entire student teaching aspects of it, where the state picked up and began
pay the individual supervising teacher, cooperating teacher, whatever you will, the stipend, I think it was $200.
And that was a major change.
It subsequently got taken off again, didn't it?
Yes, yes, yes.
Because I know our district is one of the few that still pays it, but they just pay it.
The district itself pays it.
Yes, and that's unfortunate.
I find the state putting their
heavy hands in trying to operate a college of education in areas where they really do not belong, which is in the area of curriculum.
But in the support area of student teaching support, it's unfortunate that they got out of it.
That was probably one of the major changes, this shifting over from the university supporting it to the state supporting it.
that of course enhanced the student teaching program, and we were able to
make, I would say, good adjustments with the local public schools.
I think the relationships we've had with both Bryan and College Station have always been good.
Now, of course, we have moved out beyond it because of the volume we have, and we have established some excellent facilities, I understand, in Houston.
I believe they're trying to host them in San Antonio.
We already have 12 this semester.
So we're moving across the state, which is where we belong.
The other major change, and again, the state comes into the picture, because the state of Texas has had a history of attempting to control, I think is the best word I can use,
the process of educating people to be teachers in the state of Texas.
And Texas A&M has always been in the forefront in indicating that we are an agent of the state and one of our functions is to turn out students to become teachers.
and that we are professionals.
We have a better feel for what is needed than some legislature who is operating and being pushed by various groups.
And that this position is one that should be held even to the point of, you might say, almost political confrontation with the state.
And I speak in terms of the confrontation

the then dean, Dean Hubert, and others had in the state when the state attempted to impose what they called competency-based teacher education or performance-based teacher education as the sole method of training teachers.
This would have created consternation in their, and I'll use the term very clearly, in their ignorance.
They felt that they could go into
the humanities and tell the history teacher what his or her objectives were to be and how they were to achieve it.
And of course this went over like a proverbial lead balloon.
It eventually, and it was a long story and that's a beautiful one for a dissertation for somebody down the line, but eventually
it was determined that the state was way off base in doing this and saying that was the only way it could be done.
And that shackle was released from the colleges.
And I think the college, Texas A&M University, took a strong stand in that position and should be congratulated for it.
I understand that today we now are facing something similar to it, where the state is mandating the maximum number of hours and so on and so forth.
And how this will come out, I really don't know.
But I know this, as sure as I'm sitting right here, that the people that will be hurt are the students in the state of Texas down the line 15, 20 years from now.
We just .
are two now, and what area are we working in specifically?
Well, we're in changes that impacted the College of Education and what might have cost them in the external environment, societal changes, or like you said, the political.
This was definitely all of the political influences that you're talking about.
Philosophical, maybe there might have been some.
What?

I think the philosophical basis was that we took pride in the fact that there had been gathered what we considered to be a top flight faculty, and that we indicated very strongly that the faculty should be the ultimate decision makers as to the curriculum
needed, and not some off-campus group.
And fortunately, the administration supported us.
I'm talking about the university administration supported the college in its approach.
And we could not have done it, I don't believe, without the support of the university.
At that time, as it is now, the mission of the college was still foremost, and it was the teaching, the research, and the service.
In the two eras that you were, and I'm calling the Hubert era and the Corrigan era because it was almost 10 distinct years for each one so far, was there a change in emphasis on any of those?
Was there more towards research or more towards teaching, or were they balanced fairly well under both?
administrations?
If I had to come down, I would come down and decide that yes, in that aspect, the balance was maintained.
One of the areas that I recall that illustrated this
was the area of what should be required of the Ed.D.

as compared to what should be required for the Ph.D. And when the language requirements for the Ph.D. more or less went by the board and they brought in other areas, statistics and other things that the person could
used to show competence to become the PhD title.
There was a language requirement you had to take beforehand?
Oh, yes.
PhD required language.
And I remember vividly everyone, of course, not everyone, most everyone felt that that was the most difficult thing to overcome for the PhD.
And up to and including

an actual program that took place and had some students involved in it, in which the Czechoslovakian language department set up an area of coursework, more or less through a summer type of thing and other things.
If the individual showed confidence at the end of the set of programs or courses that he or she took, they would then be certified.
And this was just one of the many ploys that the people used trying to overcome this hurdle.
Was this a PhD in education?
Was it just in one department?
Or was the PhD requirement in all the departments very similar?
The PhD requirement in
all of the departments that could offer the PhD, it was similar.
And the college then, when this surfaced, the college went through a pretty good review program of what should be required.
And they came up with some very, I think, good standards to show this.
what would be required for the PhD and what would be required for the EdD.
Is that pretty much what's in place at this time, you think?
As far as I know, I think it is.
This is a struggle that is pretty well ended by now, but many universities went through it.
I think in terms of the University of Illinois, the University of Illinois, for the PhD, in addition to the language, they had a
don't hold me to these figures, would take 34 hours beyond the master's degree was sufficient for the coursework, plus the language.
If you went the EDD route, it was 68 hours.
And they just doubled the language.
They just doubled the hours requirement if you wanted to go that way.
And our college was trying to get the distinction between the dissertation, and that was Hubert's main point,
that one of the major things would be the dissertation would be a completely different form for the PhD and the EdD.
And I'll do violence to his philosophy, I know, but I'm trying to recall what it was.
Basically, the EdD could be a study that would be useful for the practicing professional.
And it could be limited to a school district, a state, or some small area.
The PhD, I wouldn't say would have to be impractical, but would not be limited to and would not normally be that type of thing.
But the major thing that Dean Hubert and the faculty were after was, some of the faculty anyway, was that the research should be germane to the national or international level.
could be generalized, and your sample must be nationwide, so that the usual way of doing your research would not normally fill that type of thing.
Now, whether this still is in existence, I don't know, but there was a great deal of discussion, and
But that was the major recollection I have of that area.
And what the current difference is, I don't know.
During the time that you were here as a professor and then in the administration as well, there was tremendous growth in the College of Education.
Did that have any effect on the way that you were able to work with the students?
growth, the major growth, came after I kind of moved up in 72, I believe it was, into the associate dean office of student affairs.
And the growth at that time was actually
a problem for the college.
We were, as the university started bringing in a goodly large number of students, some of the students, to be brutally frank, did not belong at a competitive university such as Texas A&M.
And after a year or so attempting some of the
more rigorous curriculum, the sciences, the engineering, the students would find themselves on probation, below two point, this type of thing.
And there was a feeling on the part of the campus that the College of Education would make an ideal, and I'm being very pejorative, dumping ground for that type of student.
And the difficulty we ran into was that many of the students who had been chewed up by the system really were good students and had just made mistakes or had just not really found themselves.
And then there were a considerable number of students who were just flat not interested.
And the problem came in that the volume
made it difficult to find out which category a student might logically fit.
So the dean's office at the time was the control point as to whether a student would or would not be permitted to come into the college.
The college fought successfully to
like this control.
There were actions that people were trying to say that any student could go to any other college and that you had to accept them.
And this was eventually determined that the college would make the decision as to whether a student could or could not be admitted.
And that once a student was enrolled in the university, it didn't mean they had carte blanche to go to any college.
And it's politics, pure and simple.
But the College of Education did not need a reputation for becoming the dumping ground for the other students.
We were attempting to establish our own standards.
One of the things that the college did, and it was a very thorough review before it was done, and that was to
require a 2.25 minimum grade point average.
To transfer or just to enter?
To enter at the junior level.
And the dean's office was given authority
make exceptions and so on and so forth, and put them on probation and trials and this.
We had all kinds of varieties of ways.
Do you know when that occurred, more or less?
I can find out.
Ah.
Early on.
Seventy-four, seventy-five, somewhere around there.
Okay, in the early seventies.
And the other colleges were not very happy about it, but we could cite the need for
competent individuals and so on and so forth and this type of thing.
Did they have the same procedure or the same criteria as the other colleges, or were they forced to admit anybody they wanted to?
I mean, that they wanted to in.
You mean the other colleges?
Uh-huh.
No, eventually they all accepted the fact that the college would be the determining factor.
Sure.
trend was to go into the sciences and others and then come out of them.
We had a few that came into college and then went to the sciences.
In other words, it was primarily a one-way traffic.
And as I say, we realized that many of them were excellent students, and they became good teachers, I believe.
And others were just... Well, even now, the numbers that Brian Cole was sharing with me about the size of a freshman class in the College of Education
The senior is astounding.
I was very surprised.
That trend, very few youngsters come to education straight out of high school.
Very few.
They come to it as a result of trying various other areas and then finally deciding that this is the area.
And again, it's still the same problem.
Someone has to make the decision.
Is the fellow or the person, the woman, serious, or are they just looking for a place to be able to stay in?
At the time that you were involved with the college, was there much collaboration among the departments within the college and then outside of the college with others?
Well, of course, the collaboration came, and this is a distinction I think I can make,
King Hubert was sitting there, and Dean Corrigan was sitting over here.
The collaboration came in different manners.
The major vehicle for collaboration was this poly-pound, the policy committee meeting, which was the meeting of the dean, the associate deans, all the department heads.
And this was usually held, I think it was every Tuesday at 10 o'clock.
And if you have never gotten those meetings, the copies of those meetings, it's quite likely that they're over in the archives.
And they would give you precise data and information that you cannot get from, you know, old Codger's recall, which is a very poor way of recalling it.
But that, if I recall, one of the functions I had was retiring records.
and putting them into the archives, we normally always had copies of the policy committee meetings.
And they were held weekly, generally, pretty religiously.
And this was where the collaboration, cooperation, came in.
The style of the two deans is the point that I think I'll move into now, and that is that with Dean Yilbert, he had a style which was more directive in nature.
He felt that his role in the leadership of the college was to provide the clear-cut goal and direction, and this is the area
who we should go.
And generally, he had a very clear outline of the program that he wanted and the direction he wanted the college to go.
And the policy committee meetings under Dean Hubert were more informative to be told and to be made aware of
areas that we were going to move into, or areas that we were going to change in this type of way.
Who attended those?
The department heads.
All the department heads, the dean, and the associate deans.
They were actually, as I say, that was the policy committee.
They made it.
But always, usually, Hubert would bring an agenda.
Frequently, there would be a discussion type of thing
But the direction was usually fairly clear.
When Corrigan came, there was 180 degree change.
Now, a problem was outlined.
And the question was, where do we go?
And it was very interesting to watch the department head struggle with that.
Because the day before, they had not had to make these kinds of decisions.
And I admire both men.
I've enjoyed their acquaintances.
But Dean Corrigan stayed with it and forced the department heads and then the faculty to make decisions.
And completely different styles of leadership.
Two very effective styles of leadership.
I would be... Theory-wise, what would you, how would you... Theory-wise, you're talking to a man who spent most of his adult life in the military.
I like a leader who says, there it is, that's what we're going for, let's go.
Let's talk about it, but let's go.
I find that I have an old saying, it's called the pooling of ignorance, when you get too much of the other, because there are so many facets to a problem that are not
available for the department head.
True.
So it's hard for them to be aware.
So it's really hard.
I think you need a system whereby they would
